[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(9) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "And they made a proclamation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "uttered a voice",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cry",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ")",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": " in Judah.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The phrase (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "nathan qôl",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") occurs here only in this sense. (Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 1:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "To bring in to the Lord.—Comp. 2Chronicles 24:6. The meaning is, To bring into the Temple, for the Lord.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "To bring in to the Lord.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 24:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The meaning is, To bring into the Temple, for the Lord.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The collection.—Tax, or impost.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "The collection.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Tax, or ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "impost.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "This verse, and the next one also, are peculiar to the chronicle. The writer is fond of dwelling on the willingness of the people in the good old time to contribute to the cause of religion; doubtless, by way of suggestion to his own contemporaries. (Comp. 1Chronicles 29:6; 1Chronicles 29:9; 1Chronicles 29:14.)",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "This verse, and the next one also, are peculiar to the chronicle. The writer is fond of dwelling on the willingness of the people in the good old time to contribute to the cause of religion; doubtless, by way of suggestion to his own contemporaries. (Comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 29:6",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 29:9",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "; ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1Chronicles 29:14",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".)",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In Kings we read: “And the priests, the warders of the threshold, used to put into it all the money that was brought into the house of the Lord.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "In Kings we read: ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "“",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "And the priests, the warders of the threshold, used to put into it all the money that was brought into the house of the Lord.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Until they had made an end.—This is correct. The same phrase recurs, 2Chronicles 31:1. The ancient versions wrongly give “until it was filled.” Killāh does not mean “to make full,” as is asserted in Lange’s Commentary, but to finish any action.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "Until they had made an end.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—This is correct. The same phrase recurs, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "2Chronicles 31:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". The ancient versions wrongly give “until it was filled.” ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "Killāh",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " does not mean “to make full,” as is asserted in Lange’s Commentary, but ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "to finish",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " any action.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
